\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1: Distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This problem concerns distributions as defined in the notes: continuous
 linear functionals 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 from test functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 is the set of infinitely differentiable functions with compact support
 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

 outside some region with finite diameter [differing for different 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

], i.e.
 outside some finite interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 in 1d).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For a classical function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 to form a regular distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)\phi(x)dx$
\end_inset

, we must have a finite integral 
\begin_inset Formula $|f\{\phi\}|<\infty$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

.
 In this notes, it was claimed to be sufficient that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

locally integrable:
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}|f(x)|dx<\infty$
\end_inset

 for all intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
 Show this.
 (That is, prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}|f(x)|dx<\infty$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $|f\{\phi\}|<\infty$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Hint: just bound 
\begin_inset Formula $|f\{\phi\}|$
\end_inset

 above.
 You may the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi(x)|$
\end_inset

 has a maximum value since 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is continuous and compactly supported, by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

extreme value theorem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of analysis.)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The converse is also true: if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 locally integrable, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 is not defined for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, but you need not prove this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In this part, you will consider the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\begin{cases}
\ln|x| & x\neq0\\
0 & x=0
\end{cases}$
\end_inset

 and its (weak) derivative, which is connected to something called the Cauchy
 Principal Value.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

